semantic_equivalence_artifact.original_latex_theorem:
\label{l:infinite definable functions with real parameters} 
Let $P=\def\rf@num{X}\def\rf@den{E}\mathpalette\rfr@c\relax$ and $Q=\def\rf@num{Y}\def\rf@den{F}\mathpalette\rfr@c\relax$ be two $A^*${\hyp}hyperdefinable sets and $f$ an $\bigwedge_{A^*}${\hyp}definable partial function from $P$ to $Q$. Then, for any $\bigwedge_{A^*}${\hyp}definable sets $V\subseteq P$ and $W\subseteq Q$, $f[V]$ and $f^{-1}[W]$ are $\bigwedge_{A^*}${\hyp}definable. 
\begin{proof} It is enough to check that the projection maps satisfy the proposition. It is trivial that $\proj^{-1}_P[V]=V\times Q$ is $\bigwedge_{A^*}${\hyp}definable for any $\bigwedge_{A^*}${\hyp}definable subset $V$. On the other hand, if $V\subseteq P\times Q$ is $\bigwedge_{A^*}${\hyp}definable, by compactness, $\Sigma(x)=\{\exists y\mathrel{} \bigwedge \Delta(x,y)\sth \Delta\subseteq \underline{V}\mbox{ finite}\}$ defines $\quot^{-1}_P[\proj_P[V]]$. 
\end{proof}

