semantic_equivalence_artifact.original_latex_theorem:
\label{l:lemma normal coverings}
Let $X$ be a topological space and $\{P_n\}_{n\in\N}$ a closed coherent covering with $P_n\subseteq P_{n+1}$ for each $n\in\N$. Suppose that $P_n$ is normal for each $n\in\N$. Then, $X$ is normal. %Similarly, if $P_n$ is perfectly normal for each $n\in\N$. Then, $X$ is perfectly normal.
\begin{proof} Let $V$ and $W$ be closed disjoint subsets of $X$. Take the continuous map $g:\ V\sqcup W\rightarrow\{-1,1\}$ given by $g_{\mid V}=1$ and $g_{\mid W}=-1$. By recursion, using Tietze's Theorem \cite[Theorem 35.1]{munkres1999topology}, we construct a chain $(f_n)_{n\in\N}$ of continuous maps $f_n:\ P_n\rightarrow [-1,1]$, each one extending $g_{\mid P_n}$. Taking $f=\bigcup f_n$, we get a continuous map separating $V$ and $W$. 
\end{proof}

