{\textnormal{{\cite[Lemma 5.1]{hrushovski2022beyond}}}} \label{l:commensurator} Let $G$ be a group and $\Lambda\subseteq G$ an approximate subgroup. Then, $\mathrm{Comm}(\Lambda)=\bigcup \{\Lambda'\subseteq G$ approximate $\mathrm{subgroup}\sth \Lambda'$ and $\Lambda$ are commensurable$\}$ and $\mathrm{Comm}(G)\leq G$.
%\begin{proof} Take $g,h\in \mathrm{Comm}(\Lambda)$. By \cref{commensurability arithmetic}(2,7), $\Lambda g\sim \Lambda$ and $\Lambda h\sim \Lambda$. Hence, using \cref{commensurability arithmetic}(2,5,7), $hg^{-1}\Lambda gh^{-1}\sim\Lambda gh^{-1}\sim \Lambda h^{-1}\sim \Lambda$, so $gh^{-1}\in\mathrm{Comm}(\Lambda)$, concluding that $\mathrm{Comm}(\Lambda)$ is a subgroup. Also, for any $g\in \Lambda$, $\Lambda g\subseteq \Lambda^2\subsetsim \Lambda$, so $\Lambda g\subsetsim \Lambda$. As $\Lambda$ is symmetric, we also get $\Lambda g^{-1}\subsetsim \Lambda$, so $\Lambda\subsetsim \Lambda g$ by \cref{commensurability arithmetic}(5). Thus, we conclude that $\Lambda\sim \Lambda g$ for any $g\in\Lambda$, i.e. $\Lambda\subseteq \mathrm{Comm}(\Lambda)$. By \cref{commensurability arithmetic}(5), if $\Lambda\sim \Lambda'$ and $g\in \mathrm{Comm}(\Lambda')$, then $\Lambda g\sim\Lambda' g\sim\Lambda'\sim\Lambda$ . Thus, $g\in\mathrm{Comm}(\Lambda)$ by \cref{commensurability arithmetic}(2). As $g$ is arbitrary, we conclude that $\Lambda'\subseteq\mathrm{Comm}(\Lambda')\subseteq \mathrm{Comm}(\Lambda)$. Consequently, $\bigcup \{\Lambda'$ approximate subgroup $\sth \Lambda'\sim\Lambda\}\subseteq \mathrm{Comm}(\Lambda)$. Finally, if $g\in\mathrm{Comm}(\Lambda)$, $g^{-1}\in\mathrm{Comm}(\Lambda)$ too. Then, $\Lambda g^{-1} \sim \Lambda$ and $\Lambda g\sim \Lambda$ by \cref{commensurability arithmetic}(2,7). Thus, $g\Lambda\cup\{1\}\cup \Lambda g^{-1}\sim \Lambda$ by \cref{commensurability arithmetic}(3,6). Now, $\Lambda'\coloneqq g\Lambda \cup\{1\}\cup\Lambda g^{-1}$ is a symmetric set. Also, $(\Lambda')^2=(g\Lambda)^2\cup (\Lambda g^{-1})^2\cup \Lambda^2\cup g\Lambda^2g^{-1}\cup \Lambda'\sim \Lambda\cup (g\Lambda)^2\cup (\Lambda g^{-1})^2$ by \cref{commensurability arithmetic}(3,6). Now, $g\Lambda g\Lambda\sim \Lambda g\Lambda\sim \Lambda^2\sim \Lambda$ by \cref{commensurability arithmetic}(5,7). Similarly, we get $(\Lambda g^{-1})^2\sim \Lambda$. Therefore, by \cref{commensurability arithmetic}(2,3,6),  we conclude that $\Lambda'$ is an approximate subgroup commensurable to $\Lambda$, so $g\in\bigcup\{\Lambda'\mathrm{\ approximate\ subgroup}\sth \Lambda'\sim\Lambda\}$. As $g$ is arbitrary, we conclude that $\mathrm{Comm}(\Lambda)=\bigcup \{\Lambda'\mathrm{\ approximate\ subgroups}\sth \Lambda'\sim\Lambda\}$. 
%\end{proof}

