\label{t:logic existence of minimal lie core}
Let $G$ be a piecewise $A${\hyp}hyperdefinable group with a generic piece modulo $G^{00}_A$ and $(K_1,H_1)$ an $A${\hyp}Yamabe pair of $G$. Then, $G$ has a minimal $A${\hyp}Yamabe pair $(K,H)$ smaller than or equal to $(K_1,H_1)$. Furthermore, $H\subseteq U^2$ for any $U$ containing $K_1$ such that $\def\rf@num{U}\def\rf@den{G^{00}_A}\mathpalette\rfr@c\relax$ is a clopen neighbourhood of $\def\rf@num{K_1}\def\rf@den{G^{00}_A}\mathpalette\rfr@c\relax$ in the global logic topology. 
\begin{proof} Clear from \cref{c:minimal yamabe pairs}, using the Generic Set Lemma (\cref{t:generic set lemma}), and \cref{t:piecewise hyperdefinable and local compactness,p:compact locally hyperdefinable}. %We assume without loss of generality that $G^{00}_A$ is trivial and $G$ is small. By \cref{t:generic set lemma}, $G$ is locally hyperdefinable. By \cref{piecewise hyperdefinable and local compactness}, $G$ is a locally compact topological group with the global logic topology. By \cref{minimal yamabe pairs}, $G$ has a minimal Yamabe pair $(K,H)$ smaller than $(K_1,H_1)$ and $H\subseteq U^2$ for any clopen neighbourhood $U$ of $K_1$ in the global logic topology. By \cref{compact locally hyperdefinable}, $K$ is $\bigwedge${\hyp}definable, so $(K,H)$ is a minimal $A${\hyp}Yamabe pair.
\end{proof}

