semantic_equivalence_artifact.original_latex_theorem:
\label{l:minimal yamabe pair and aperiodic component} Let $G$ be a piecewise $0${\hyp}hyperdefinable group with a generic piece and $G^{\mathrm{ap}}$ the aperiodic component of $G$. Let $(K,H)$ be a minimal $A${\hyp}Yamabe pair of $G$ with Lie core $\pi_{H/K}:\ H\rightarrow L$. Then, $G^{\mathrm{ap}}\cap H\leq K$.  
\begin{proof}  Let $B$ be the small set of parameters with $A\subseteq B$ such that the $B${\hyp}logic topology of $\def\rf@num{G}\def\rf@den{G^{00}_A}\mathpalette\rfr@c\relax$ is its global logic topology. Denote by $\mathrm{cl}_B$ the closure in the $B${\hyp}logic topology of $G$. We define by recursion the sequence $(J_\alpha)_{\alpha\in\Ord}$ of piecewise $\bigwedge_B${\hyp}definable normal subgroups of $G$ given by $J_0=G^{00}_A$, $J_{\gamma}=\mathrm{cl}_B(\bigcup_{i\in \gamma} J_i)$ for $\gamma$ limit and $J_{\alpha+1}=\mathrm{cl}_B(\bigcup \mathcal{K}_\alpha)$ where $\mathcal{K}_\alpha$ is the family of piecewise $\bigwedge${\hyp}definable normal subgroups which are $\bigwedge${\hyp}definable modulo $J_\alpha$.

\begin{claim} For $\alpha_0\in\Ord$ large enough, $J_\alpha=G^{\mathrm{ap}}$ for any $\alpha\geq \alpha_0$.
\begin{proof} We prove inductively that $J_\alpha\subseteq G^{\mathrm{ap}}$ for any $\alpha\in\Ord$. Obviously, $J_0\subseteq G^{\mathrm{ap}}$. For $\gamma$ limit, assuming that $J_i\subseteq G^{\mathrm{ap}}$ for each $i\in \gamma$, as $G^{\mathrm{ap}}$ is piecewise $\bigwedge_B${\hyp}definable, we get that $J_\gamma\subseteq G^{\mathrm{ap}}$. Finally, assuming that $J_\alpha\subseteq G^{\mathrm{ap}}$, we have a piecewise bounded $\bigwedge${\hyp}definable onto homomorphism $\pi:\ \def\rf@num{G}\def\rf@den{J_{\alpha}}\mathpalette\rfr@c\relax\rightarrow \def\rf@num{G}\def\rf@den{G^{\mathrm{ap}}}\mathpalette\rfr@c\relax$. As $\def\rf@num{G}\def\rf@den{G^{\mathrm{ap}}}\mathpalette\rfr@c\relax$ is aperiodic, we have that every piecewise $\bigwedge${\hyp}definable normal subgroup of $G$ which is $\bigwedge${\hyp}definable modulo $J_{\alpha}$ must be contained in $G^{\mathrm{ap}}$. Therefore, $\bigcup \mathcal{K}_\alpha\subseteq G^{\mathrm{ap}}$, concluding that $J_{\alpha+1}\subseteq G^{\mathrm{ap}}$. 

On the other hand, as there is a small amount of piecewise $\bigwedge_B${\hyp}definable normal subgroups of $G$, for large $\alpha_0$, we must have $J_{\alpha_0+1}=J_{\alpha_0}$. In particular, that means that $\def\rf@num{G}\def\rf@den{J_{\alpha_0}}\mathpalette\rfr@c\relax$ is an aperiodic locally compact topological group with its global logic topology, so $G^{\mathrm{ap}}\leq J_{\alpha_0}$. Thus,  $G^{\mathrm{ap}}=J_\beta$ for $\beta\geq \alpha_0$. \claimqed
\end{proof}
\end{claim}

Now, we prove by induction that, for any $\alpha\in \Ord$, we have $J_\alpha\cap H\leq K$. Obviously, $J_0\cap H\leq K$. For $\gamma$ limit, assuming that $J_i\cap H\leq K$ for any $i\in \gamma$, we have $H\cap \bigcup_{i\in\gamma} J_i\leq K$. Therefore, $H\cap J_{\gamma}=\mathrm{cl}_B(H\cap \bigcup_{i\in\gamma}J_i)\subseteq K$, as $H$ is clopen and $K$ is closed in the $B${\hyp}logic topology. Finally, assuming $J_\alpha\cap H\leq K$, we have a piecewise bounded $\bigwedge${\hyp}definable onto homomorphism $\pi:\ \def\rf@num{H}\def\rf@den{J_\alpha}\mathpalette\rfr@c\relax\rightarrow L=\def\rf@num{H}\def\rf@den{K}\mathpalette\rfr@c\relax$. As $L$ is aperiodic, we have that $H\cap \bigcup\mathcal{K}_\alpha\subseteq K$. Therefore, $H\cap J_{\alpha+1}=\mathrm{cl}_B(H\cap \bigcup \mathcal{K}_\alpha)\subseteq K$, as $H$ is clopen and $K$ is closed in the $B${\hyp}logic topology. In particular, by the claim, we conclude that $G^{\mathrm{ap}}\cap H\leq K$.  
\end{proof}

